# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: classic-tetris-world-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] On February 1, 2013, the company announced that due to their recent co-development efforts with Nintendo, they were undergoing a change in internal structure.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] As a result, the company took on its current name.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] At the same time, Kameoka left to form a new studio, Brownies.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] Since the 2010s, the company has mainly worked as a support studio to Nintendo EPD, with its staff mainly consisting of artists, game designers, and programmers.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] 1-Up was founded on June 30, 2000 as **Brownie Brown**, and consisted of many 2D artists formerly of Square.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] Founders Shinichi Kameoka and Kouji Tsuda had previously worked on the *Mana* series on the Game Boy and Super NES platforms.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] They left Square due to "differing ideals." The studio's name came from the Brownies, fairies of Scottish folklore said to be hardworking and friendly, which Kameoka believed fit the team's style (a Brownie is featured in the studio's logo).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] He elaborated that he wanted to make Game Boy Advance games, leading to the creation of Brownie Brown.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] The company's first original creation was the Japan-only *Magical Vacation* for the Game Boy Advance, which was released in 2001.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] Another popular title developed by Brownie Brown was *Sword of Mana*, which was created for and published by Square Enix.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] Thought to be a new title in the *Seiken Densetsu* series, it was actually an enhanced remake of the first game in the series, *Seiken Densetsu: Final Fantasy Gaiden* (known as *Mystic Quest* in Europe and *Final Fantasy Adventure* in North America).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] The company has also been credited with the development of *Mother 3* in a collaborative effort with Shigesato Itoi and HAL Laboratory for the Game Boy Advance, and *Magical Starsign* (*Magical Vacation: When the Five Stars Align* in Japan) for the Nintendo DS.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] Brownie Brown expressed interest in a Nintendo DS port of *Mother 3* if Nintendo asked them to make it, and that they would like it to be enjoyed by fans abroad.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] While the company only developed games for Nintendo's handheld consoles up to this point, the company had previously announced a title for the GameCube, named *Gofuku*, which was scheduled for release in 2005 and announced alongside *Magical Starsign*.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] The company later released *Blue Dragon Plus* for the Nintendo DS, developed alongside Mistwalker, and entered into the downloadable games market in 2009 with *A Kappa's Trail*, a DSiWare game.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] Upon the changes, Kameoka left 1-Up Studio to found Brownies, seeking to make original games.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] In the same year, Yoshiaki Koizumi became part of the board of directors of the company as one of its directors.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/1-up-studio] In 2020, the company moved its headquarters to the new Nintendo Tokyo Office building at Kanda Square, Tokyo with Nintendo EPD Tokyo, Nintendo PTD Tokyo, HAL Laboratory Head Office and Tokyo R&D Center, and Game Freak.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2007-in-esports] In Major League Gaming, Team Final Boss beat Team Carbon to win the MLG Las Vegas 2007 National Championship.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2007-in-esports] In the Championship Gaming Series their series began in 2007, with the 2007 Championship Gaming Series season.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2007-in-esports] At the time it was the most expensive esports tournament of all time.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2013-in-esports] This article documents the year 2013 in esports.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2014-in-esports] List of events in 2014 in esports (also known as professional gaming).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2016-in-esports] List of events in 2016 in eSports (also known as professional gaming).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The **2017 Visa Vegas eRace** was an eSports Formula E race held on January 7, 2017, at The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino in Las Vegas, Nevada, as part of the Sports Business Innovation Summit at the 2017 Consumer Electronics Show.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] This race, unlike others, did not count towards the 2016-17 season and was not held on a real track.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Ten sim racers—competitors who typically enter simulation racing video games—raced against regular series drivers on a simulated course for a $1 million total prize fund, a record in eSports racing history.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The race consisted of two races: a 14-lap qualifying race for the slowest 20 qualifiers to determine positions 11 to 20 for the 20-lap main race; and a 20-lap main race.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] An earlier qualifying session, divided into five groups of six cars, determined the first ten starting positions.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Bono Huis, a Dragon sim driver, led every session and won the event from pole position.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] António Félix da Costa, a professional driver, won the earlier qualifying race.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis led for the majority of the race until the mandatory virtual pit stops to change into a second car, when Mahindra's Olli Pahkala took over.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala finished first on the road after leading the final five laps, but he was penalised 12 seconds after it was discovered that a software bug allowed him to use FanBoost for longer than allowed.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Felix Rosenqvist, the highest-placed professional driver for Mahindra, took second, while Pakhala's penalty dropped him to third.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The eRace received mixed reviews in the media.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Those who criticised the race criticised its organisation because multiple technical issues caused a half-hour delay in the main event, and one driver was forced to withdraw from both races due to simulator issues.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Positive reviewers expressed their belief that the event's consequences could lead to a professional eSports racing series and aid in the resolution of accessibility issues, as well as for others to use it as an alternative career to traditional motor racing.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Following the eRace, some sim racers were adopted into the teams to which they were assigned, assisting their real-life development through car testing and advice.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Luis Pachon, the founder of the Madrid-based start-up company Cloud Sport, proposed the idea for an eRace in Las Vegas to Formula E (FE) CEO Alejandro Agag, who quickly understood Pachon's intention and began work soon after.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] *iRacing* was reportedly an early contender for an association with FE, but the costs of laser scanning the track, and the lack of a wider benefit of putting in the effort of constructing the circuit, meant it was not cost effective.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Agag revealed the eRace plans to *Reuters* in June 2016, and announced that it would take place during the 2017 Consumer Electronics Show (CES).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] FE had previously held eRaces at all championship rounds, in which spectators competed against professional racing drivers in the eVillage of the hosting race track.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The eRace was officially confirmed at the 2016 London ePrix the following month.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] It was held on January 7, 2017, as part of CES' Sport Business Innovation Summit at The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino, but it did not count towards the 2016–17 championship and no points were awarded.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] For this event, FE partnered with ELEAGUE and featured commentary from Jack Nicholls and Dario Franchitti.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The eRace featured 20 FE competitors from the regular season grid and ten sim racing drivers who qualified for the event by competing in the Road to Vegas Challenge, a four-race elimination contest held between October 16 and December 4, 2016.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Former Formula Ford 1600 driver Graham Carroll and iRacing world champion Greger Huttu qualified first and second for the eRace.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Each of the ten sim drivers was assigned to one of the ten genuine FE teams at random.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] For realism, each participant wore a flame-proof race suit and drove identical virtual cars, with the only difference being team liveries and personal numbers for identification.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Pit stops to virtually switch to a second car were mandatory.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The race was regulated by FE's sporting director, and motorsport's world governing body, the Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The total prize fund was $1 million (the largest in eSports racing history), and was broadcast on the live streaming platform Twitch.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Cloud Sport designed the 3.14-mile (5.05 km) long anti-clockwise track, which was publicly unveiled on January 6.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Drivers started on South Las Vegas Boulevard, passing hotels and casino resorts such as the Luxor and the MGM Grand.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Cloud Sport supplied and regulated the Playseat simulation equipment which operated on the racing video game *rFactor 2.* Thrustmaster TS-PC steering wheels and T3PA pedals were fitted to the equipment.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The stewards sealed and approved all computers to ensure parity.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] External ports were blocked to prevent anyone from connecting personal components.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Drivers were unable to feel G-forces during the race, so Cloud Sport programmed the vehicles to respond to the inertia created by sudden acceleration.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] This created a realistic driving experience, as vehicles tilted onto three wheels during sharp cornering, and the cars' performance deteriorated when they were damaged.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The Vegas eRace was heavily promoted beforehand.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] If all you do is race on simulators at home, then maybe they are pretty good!." According to Mahindra's Felix Rosenqvist, the sim racers would have an advantage due to their experience, but it would not be as significant after learning the circuit.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Four practice sessions were held before the qualification race on January 7.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The first session, held on January 6, lasted half an hour and was attended by sim drivers, followed by an identically timed session for professional racing drivers fifteen minutes later.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] On the morning of January 7, the final two sessions for sim and professional drivers each lasted fifteen minutes.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Bono Huis set the fastest time for Dragon in the combined opening practice session, 1 minute, 28.456 seconds, half a second faster than anyone else.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] His closest rival was professional driver Rosenqvist, who finished second, ahead of third-placed Graham Carroll and Virgin's José María López in fourth.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Piquet was fifth, ahead of sixth-placed António Félix da Costa.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Sam Bird, Enzo Bonito, Olli Pahkala and Frijns rounded out the top ten fastest drivers in the session.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis again led the combined time sheets in the second practice session, this time with a lap of 1 minute, 28.142 seconds, more than half a second faster than second-placed Frijns; Rosenqvist was third, Félix da Costa was fourth, Petar Brljak was fifth, and Graham Carroll was sixth.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala was seventh, Bonito eighth, David Greco ninth and López tenth.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Saturday afternoon's 50 minute qualifying session was divided into five groups of six cars.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The groups were determined by a lottery system and were permitted six minutes of on-track activity.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The fastest five overall competitors in all five groups participated in a "Super Pole" session with one driver on the track at any time going out in reverse order from fifth to first.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Each of the five drivers was limited to one timed lap and the starting order was determined by their' fastest times.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] (Super Pole from first to fifth, and group qualifying from sixth to tenth).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis continued to top every session throughout the eRace meeting and achieved pole position with a lap of 1 minute, 28.631 seconds.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] He received a $25,000 automatic award for his achievement.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Rosenqvist, whose fastest lap was two-tenths of a second slower, joined Huis on the front row.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Sim racers rounded out the top ten, with Aleksi Uusi-Jaakkola third and Graham Carroll fourth.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Greco finished fifth out of five super pole competitors.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Sixth to tenth place went to Pahkala, Patrik Holzmann, Huttu, Bonito, and Alkesi Elomaa.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Lucas di Grassi, Ma Qinghua, Bird, Maro Engel, Jean-Éric Vergne, Jérôme d'Ambrosio, Daniel Abt, Sébastien Buemi, Mitch Evans, Stéphane Sarrazin, Loïc Duval, Nico Prost, Oliver Turvey, Adam Carroll, Petar Brjlak (who crashed during his run) and Nick Heidfeld completed the starting order.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] From 15:25 Pacific Standard Time (PST) (UTC+08:00), the slowest 20 drivers from group qualifying competed in a 14-lap qualifying race to determine positions 11 to 20 on the grid.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] D'Ambrosio failed to start due to technical problems with his racing pod.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] In a race marred by multiple crashes that resulted in several cars losing bodywork parts, López led from the start until Félix da Costa closed in on him and overtook him on the outside at turn five.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Félix da Costa led the rest of the race to finish first and start 11th in the main race.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] López finished second and Frijns came third.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Outside the top three, Piquet secured fourth and was followed closely behind by Evans and Bird in fifth and sixth.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Defending series champion Buemi took seventh ahead of di Grassi in eighth.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The final two qualifiers were Di Grassi's teammate Abt and Duval in ninth and tenth.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The "Fan Boost" feature, which provided an additional 100 kW (130 hp) of power for six seconds in the driver's second car, was a unique feature of FE.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] A fan vote determined which three drivers were allowed to use the boost.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Pakhala, López, and Greco were given the extra power for the Vegas eRace.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The race was due to begin at 16:05 PST, but due to multiple technical issues, it was delayed for half an hour and reduced from 28 to 20 laps.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Di Grassi failed to start due to a simulator control issue.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The exact number of viewers was not disclosed.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis maintained the lead from the standing start entering the first corner and began to expand a small lead over Rosenqvist in the opening laps, who could not maintain the leader's pace.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Towards the end of lap one, Holzmann clipped the outside wall out of the final corner, speared across the start/finish straight, and collected Félix da Costa, ending both drivers' chances of a podium finish.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Holzmann retired, but Félix da Costa continued despite minor car damage.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Piquet dropped to 17th on the first lap, but returned to 14th by lap seven.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] By the third lap, Bird had moved up to sixth.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The mandatory virtual pit stops required all drivers to change cars, began at the end of lap seven, when Bird entered the pit lane.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala left a multi-car battle for third with Uusi-Jaakkola, Greco, and Graham Carroll at the conclusion of the next lap in order to make his mandatory pit stop.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala left with a clear track ahead of him, and because no other driver was impeding him, he set a series of fast lap times.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] On the tenth lap, Graham Carroll got a run on Uusi-Jaakkola leaving the final corner and steered onto the inside line into the first turn chicane.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Greco made it three abreast on the outside.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] He and Uusi-Jaakkola collided, and the latter touched Graham Carroll's left-rear wheel.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Two of the cars barrel-rolled through the trackside catch fencing and into some palm trees.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The cars glitched quickly and re-rendered themselves onto the circuit.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Both Uusi-Jaakkola and Greco had lost a wheel and dropped several positions.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Virtual racing technology meant the trio emerged unhurt from the crash and the safety car was not used.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] As the eRace progressed, race leader Huis made an error, allowing Rosenqvist to close to within less than two seconds of him.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis and Rosenqvist made their pit stops together at the end of lap fifteen and emerged in second and third places.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Pakhala lapped in the 1 minute, 24 second range, moving him to the front of the field, and requiring Huis and Rosenqvist to focus on battling for second position.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Buemi dropped outside the top ten with four laps remaining when Piquet passed him for tenth.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Ussi-Jaakkola and Bonito battled for fourth, which ended in the latter's favour in the last three laps.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala was unchallenged for the rest of the eRace, and was first to cross the start/finish line.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis held off Rosenqvist in the closing laps for second.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis and Dragon filed a complaint with the race officials following the podium ceremony.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] An examination of data shared by viewers on Twitter shortly after the race revealed that Pahkala had used FanBoost illegally for approximately five laps, rather than the maximum of five seconds due to a software bug.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Hence, Pahkala had 12 seconds added to his race time and was demoted to third.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis inherited the victory with Rosenqvist second.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Bonito finished fourth, ahead of the Finnish duo of Uusi-Jaakkola and Huttu.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] The final classified finishers were López, Bird, Abt, Piquet, Buemi, Elomaa, Frijns, Duval, Greco, Félix da Costa, and Graham Carroll.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis received $200,000 for race victory and Greco got $10,000 for setting the fastest lap.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Huis commented on the victory: "It's very exciting to be here, racing in conjunction with pro drivers during one of the most renowned tech forward events.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Media reaction to the Vegas eRace was mostly positive.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] New England Sports Network's Pat McAssey noted that FE's partnership with ELEAGUE brought sim racing to a mainstream audience and argued that eSports can potentially solve accessibility issues because some people lack the money to purchase a go-kart.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] He argued that FE could help eRacing grow and allow others to use it as an alternative career path to traditional motor racing.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Curtis Moldrich, writing for *Alphr*, echoed similar sentiments, believing that the positive outcome of the Vegas eRace was a testament to FE's forward-thinking philosophy.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Other media outlets received the race more negatively.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] It lacked any sense of real weight or drama, and tied in with the glitches affecting some of the drivers it didn't come anywhere near to producing the excitement of real racing." Jonathan M.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Gitlin of *Ars Technica* felt short-changed watching the eRace and noted the large number of complaints about the quality of the graphics in the Twitch stream.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/2017-vegas-erace] Following the event, some of the competing sim racers were adopted into their respective teams and assisted in the real-life development of their cars through testing and advising, indicating that their opinions were taken seriously, according to FE's eSports manager Matt Huxley.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The **Classic Tetris World Championship** (**CTWC**) is a video game competition series hosted by the SoCal Gaming Expo.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The competition launched in 2010, during the filming of *Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters*, to determine the world's greatest *Tetris* player.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In its first two years, the competition was held in Los Angeles, California, but was moved to Portland, Oregon, in 2012, and was held there annually through 2023 (with the exceptions of the 2020 and 2021 tournaments, held online due to the COVID-19 pandemic).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Since 2024, the tournament has been held in Pasadena, California.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The contestants play the 1989 Nintendo version of *Tetris* on Nintendo Entertainment System consoles and cathode-ray tube (CRT) video displays.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] All of the tournaments are streamed online with live-edited screens and heads-up display to improve the viewer experience.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The tournament was initially dominated by the late Jonas Neubauer, who reached the finals in the first nine iterations of the tournament, winning seven titles with accompanying T-shaped trophies.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Since 2021, the competition awards the Jonas Neubauer Memorial Trophy in his honor, a J-tetromino in gold for the champion and in silver for the runner-up.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The trophy's backside features an engraved quote of his: “If you're a high visibility player, it's on you to move the community in a positive direction”.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The competition takes place over two days, with the qualifying round on the first day and the main event on the second.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Contestants are allowed to bring their own controller, but it must be either an original, unmodified NES Controller or an aftermarket unit that is deemed a reproduction that is faithful enough.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Qualifying takes place on a fixed number of NES stations.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Entrants play "Type A" Tetris, starting on level 9 or higher, and are seeded based on their final score.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Once an entrant's game ends for any reason, their score must be recorded by a tournament scorekeeper in order to be valid.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Entrants may make as many qualifying attempts as they wish, but must return to the back of the waiting line for each one.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Entrants may also pay a fee to rent a station for one hour, which allows unlimited qualifying attempts.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In 2022, the lines were discontinued and each player could register for a two-hour time slot in which to make as many qualifying attempts as desired.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The top 32 scorers are seeded into a tournament bracket for the main event.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In 2018, 40 players were allowed to qualify, with a "Round Zero" play-off held among the bottom 16 seeds to reduce the field to 32.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Forty-eight players qualified in 2016; the top 16 seeds automatically advanced, while the remaining 32 competed in "Round Zero" to fill the other 16 slots.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In the event of multiple players maxing out (scoring 999,999 or higher), their highest non-maxout score is recorded to determine their seeding.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] This was especially utilized in 2018, when seven players maxed out, four of whom (Koji "Koryan" Nishio, Tomohiro "Green Tea" Tatejima, Jonas Neubauer and Harry Hong) maxed out twice.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Thus, the officials needed their third-highest scores just to determine the 1st to 4th seeding.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The main event is a single-elimination tournament, called the Gold Bracket, consisting of best of five head-to-head matches.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Seeds from opposite ends of the qualifying rankings are pitted against each other in the first round, with the top 16 seeds being awarded a bye.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Originally, competition games were played on unmodified NES *Tetris* game cartridges.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Beginning from the 2016 tournament, the game code was modified to be capable of displaying 7-figure score values (prior to this change, the score would 'max out' at 999,999).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Beginning from the 2023 tournament, game code was further modified such that at level 39, the speed of the falling pieces is increased to 2 cells per frame, effectively inhibiting gameplay past level 39.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Both players in a match play "Type A" Tetris, beginning on Level 18, at the same time on separate systems.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The player who reaches a higher score wins the round.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Matches between players are best-of-three or best-of-five rounds, depending on the event.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In a manner similar to the National Invitation Tournament, silver and bronze tournaments were introduced in 2020 and 2021 respectively.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Each bracket consists of 32 top-scoring players who failed to qualify for the main event.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Just as with the Gold Bracket, all games are fully broadcast and each winner will receive a smaller trophy and an interview.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In 2022, a local media outlet incorrectly identified the Silver Bracket winner as the "Tetris world champion".
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The inaugural Classic Tetris World Championship was held on August 8, 2010, at the Downtown Independent theater in Los Angeles, California.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Los Angeles was chosen because several high-ranking players lived there.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Modeled after the 1990 Nintendo World Championships, eight players completed three *Tetris* challenges to decide the two finalists.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Five of the eight seats in the semifinal were reserved for specific distinguished *Tetris* players: Jonas Neubauer, Harry Hong, Ben Mullen, Jesse Kelkar and Thor Aackerlund.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Neubauer won $1,000 after defeating Hong in the final.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The tournament was attended by Henk Rogers and a film crew for the 2011 documentary *Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters*.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The second annual championship was held at the University of Southern California's Bovard Auditorium on October 16, 2011, with financial support from Electronic Arts.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The main tournament was now a single-elimination tournament, and all matches were best-of-three.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Neubauer successfully defended his title against Alex Kerr in the final.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In addition to classic *Tetris*, tournaments were also held for EA's *Tetris* for PlayStation 3 (including both a solo and 2 vs 2 team tournament, with best-of-seven matches) and the tabletop game Tetris Link.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The 2011 tournament was expensive and poorly attended, and it was unclear if a third event would be feasible.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In what Chris Tang describes as the tournament being "saved by a miracle", the Portland Retro Gaming Expo – held at the Oregon Convention Center – made arrangements for it to be held there beginning in 2012.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Neubauer continued his winning streak in the 2012 and 2013 finals, which were now held as best-of-five matches.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] His streak was interrupted in 2014 when he was defeated by Hong, but he regained the title with his fifth championship win in 2015.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] (right) became popular online due to its enthusiastic and repetitive commentary.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Neubauer's opponent in the 2016 final was Jeff Moore, a dark horse who was performing strongly.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Moore's impressive play got the commentators "overly excited", and they enthusiastically yelled "Boom!
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Although Moore was not able to defeat Neubauer, the match became popular on YouTube, where it was parodied.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Writing for *Engadget*, James Trew credits the Neubauer–Moore match and "Boom!
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] After watching the Neubauer–Moore match on YouTube, 15-year-old Joseph Saelee became interested in *Tetris*.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] He prioritized learning a rare playstyle called hypertapping, which by 2017 had only been used competitively by two players – Thor Aackerlund and Koji "Koryan" Nishio.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] When hypertapping, the buttons on the game controller are pressed extremely rapidly with muscle tremors (rather than pressing and holding buttons).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Within one year, Saelee had set numerous world records with the technique.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Saelee, now 16 years old, entered the 2018 tournament hoping "just to qualify", without serious expectations for his first competition.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] He was much younger than most competitors, many of whom were in their thirties or forties.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] After defeating both Hong and Koryan, he had reached the final, where he would face Neubauer.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Saelee won the final 3–0, becoming the new world champion.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] He initially exited the stage emotional and speechless; Neubauer took the microphone to praise Saelee's play.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The YouTube video of the Neubauer–Saelee match, titled "16 y/o Underdog vs.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] 7-time Champ", became the most-viewed competitive *Tetris* match and is credited with popularizing hypertapping and attracting young players to *Tetris*.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] As of 2025, it has over 20 million views.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The 2018 event was shown on commercial television, with a recap airing on ESPN2.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Future recaps would air as part of ESPN8: The Ocho special programming.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In 2019, Saelee won back-to-back titles, defeating rival hypertapper Koji Nishio.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the 2020 event was held online with a different set of rules from the in-person tournaments.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Michael Artiaga (dogplayingtetris) won the final.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] He became the youngest-ever champion, aged 13 years and 16 days, defeating his 15-year-old brother Andrew Artiaga (P1xelAndy).
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Michael Artiaga scored back-to-back CTWC victories by defeating Jacob Huff in the 2021 final.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Neubauer died unexpectedly in January 2021.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The new strategy has brought in a wave of scoring records, with the world record more than quadrupling, and has seen former DAS players and hypertappers (including the Artiagas) adopt the playing style.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The 2022 tournament, held in Portland for the first time in three years, was dominated by rollers.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Eric Tolt "EricICX" defeated Justin Yu "Fractal161" to win the title three games to one.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The third game saw both players exceed 2.1 million points, with Tolt winning the game and later the crown.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The 2023 event saw Yu win his first title, coming from 0–2 down to defeat Eve "Sidnev" Commandeur of the Netherlands 3–2 in the final.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Commandeur also set the qualifying record with 16 maxouts, which was tied by both Willis Gibson "Blue Scuti" and Noah Dengler in the 2024 event.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In the 2024 tournament, now held in Pasadena, Alex Thach claimed his first title, defeating former two-time champion Michael Artiaga in a close 3:2 decider.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The 2025 tournament again was won by Thach, notably without losing a single game in bracket play.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Thach also set a new qualifying record by tying the previous 16 maxouts, but with an additional high score of 971,440 points, less than a tetris short of an unprecedented 17th maxout.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The 2026 tournament saw Michael Artiaga "dogplayingtetris" reclaim the title to secure his third world championship, defeating "meme" 3–2 in the final.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In the semifinals, Artiaga advanced after two-time defending champion Alex Thach was forced to forfeit the match due to an injury.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] With the ultimate tournament victory, Artiaga broke Thach's title streak and became the first player since Jonas Neubauer to win three world championships.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] He also became the first person to win a world championship with two different playstyles.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Since 2023, *Tetris* game code used in CTWC matches has been modified to inhibit play past level 39.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Since 2018, global CTWC stops have been officially added, many of which are directly linked to the CTWC main event in Pasadena.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Other than prizes, the winner of each global stop is sponsored to fly to Pasadena and try to qualify for the finals.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] During the expo there have been several tournaments on other systems over the years.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] There is a once-a-month online tournament called Classic Tetris Monthly (CTM) that was previously hosted on the same Twitch channel as the CTWC, but it now is hosted on MonthlyTetris.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Competitors routinely compete from around the world in CTM, which is streamed remotely and thus allows for great flexibility on the part of the competitors.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Competitive play is broken up into four categories, based on your qualifier for the month, Masters, Hopefuls, Futures, and Community.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] CTM is overseen and commentated chiefly by Keith "vandweller" Didion, who took over for Jessica "fridaywitch" Starr, the tournament's founder, in the Summer of 2018.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Starr premiered the tournament on December 3, 2017, on her personal Twitch channel, with 16 participants that had qualified in the few weeks leading up to the event.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Harry Hong, the 2014 CTWC champion, was the tournament's first victor.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Didion opened a Twitch account dedicated to CTM, called MonthlyTetris, shortly after he began hosting.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] There is a prize pool for the top performers of the Masters Division which is crowdfunded each month by donations.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Additionally, the CTM Discord server is in many ways the center of the Classic Tetris Community, serving as its primary online meeting space.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Since 2015, a Classic Tetris European Championship has been played annually in Copenhagen.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] The tournament follows a similar structure, but is played on the PAL version of NES Tetris rather than the NTSC version.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] Due to the difference in framerates, the two versions of the game (both of which are designed for the NES) are balanced differently; pieces do not fall at identical speeds on the same level between the two versions.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In addition, Delay Auto Shift (DAS) is faster in PAL compared to NTSC.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] At higher level play, this leads to significant differences in strategy and outcome.
[src:classic-tetris-world-championship/classic-tetris-world-championship] In particular, players who employ DAS as their primary strategy are able to play at the highest level.
